Key Match Events: Brandon King lashed 53 off 37 and his opening partner Johnson Charles, a pulsating 42 off 25 deliveries
Jason Holder’s 18-ball 34 at number nine overshadowed by a burdensome asking rate of 17 off the last three overs
Veteran left-hander David Warner had earlier top-scored with 70 off 36 deliveries in his 100th T20 International
Seamer Holder broke the opening stand in the eighth over when the got Inglis to hole out to mid off
David then propped up the innings in a sixth wicket partnership, posting exactly 50 off 24 balls with Matthew Wade (21)
Andre Russell grabbed three for 43, two of his wickets coming in the final over
In reply, King and Charles put the hosts’ bowling to the sword, West Indies galloping to 74 without loss off the first power-play
King belted seven fours and a six in his ninth T20I fifty while Charles carved out half-dozen fours and a six before picking out Warner on the ropes at deep cover in the ninth over

Matthews ranked among top 10 in ODI batters and bowlers

West Indies women’s captain Hayley Matthews is now ranked in the top 10 of both the One-Day International batting and bowling rankings following strong performances in the recently concluded tour of India.
West Indies star batsman Sherfane Rutherford believes his hard work and the love for his family are the main reasons behind his recent batting exploits, which have garnered widespread acclaim.

In 2024, Rutherford scored 425 runs in seven One Day International (ODI) innings at an amazing average of 106.25, leading to him being nominated for the ICC’s ODI Cricketer of the Year Award and being named in the ESPNcricinfo’s ODI Team of the Year.

While Trinidad and Tobago cricketers have excelled individually over the past year, with one regional trophy to show, 2024 was not the best in terms of results on the field or in the T&T Cricket Board’s (TTCB) “front office”.
TTCB first vice-president Arjoon Ramlal described 2024 as a challenging year administratively, but he said he is still “pretty satisfied” with what they managed to achieve over the past 12 months.
There were no gold medals in the big meets for Jereem Richards and Makaira Wallace in 2024, but both athletes are convinced the coming year can bring podium success. And maybe even a record or two.

The two were among the big winners when the Trinidad and Tobago Olympic Committee (TTOC) hosted its gala Annual Awards Ceremony, on Sunday evening. Sprinter Richards was named the TTOC’s Sportsman of the Year, while teenage cyclist Wallace won the People’s Choice award despite missing out on the Junior and Senior Sportswoman accolades at the function held at the Government Plaza Auditorium. Richards, who fell agonisingly short of an Olympic bronze medal when clocking a new national record of 43.78 seconds in the 400 metres at the Paris Olympics, now has his sights set on another landmark-- Ato Boldon’s 200m national record.
